Title : James Roberts (football and futsal)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}
{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}
'''James ("Jim") Roberts''' (born 13 August 1948) is an Australian sports and recreation advocate, former [[association football]] player and former coach of the [[Australia national futsal team|Australian national futsal team]].

== Playing career ==

Born in Sydney, Roberts played association football for [[Sydney Prague]] and [[Bankstown City Lions|Bankstown City Football Club]] and then [[Canberra City FC]] and other clubs in Canberra in the Australian Capital Territory after he moved there in 1973.

== Coaching career ==

In 1987 Roberts and [[Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)|Charles Perkins AO]] devised the first Aboriginal Futsal Cup with Canada and Roberts coached the first Australian Aboriginal indoor soccer select team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19#c312 |title=Inductees |publisher=Act Sport |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501122434/http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19 |archivedate= 1 May 2011 |df= }}</ref>
Roberts went on to coach the Australian national futsal team from 1992 until 2000. Under his stewardship, the team qualified for and competed at the [[1992 FIFA Futsal World Championship]] in Hong Kong,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/05/32/futsal_92_tr_172.pdf |title=Report: Futsal World Championship Hong Kong 1992 |publisher=FIFA |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> the [[1996 FIFA Futsal World Championship]] in Spain,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/05/25/futsal_96_tr_part2_170.pdf |title=Report: Futsal World Championship Spain 1996 |publisher=FIFA |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> and the [[2000 FIFA Futsal World Championship]] in Guatemala.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/05/21/futsal_00_tr_gua_169.pdf |title=Report: Futsal World Championship Guatemala 2000 |publisher=FIFA |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> At the time of his retirement from coaching in 2000, he was one of only four national team coaches in history to have participated in three FIFA futsal world cups. The national team played 66 games under his leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19#c312 |title=Inductees |publisher=Act Sport |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501122434/http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19 |archivedate= 1 May 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballnsw.com.au/index.php?id=149&tx_ttnews%5Byear%5D=2012&tx_ttnews%5Bmonth%5D=07&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=6788&cHash=9530fd471da3019c304614eca710b45c |title=The Aussie Futsal Fightback |publisher=Football NSW |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>

== Sport and recreation advocacy ==

In 1985, Roberts became President of ACT Sports House, a position that he held until 2003. Under his presidency, ACT Sports House became ACTSport, the peak industry body for sport in the Australian Capital Territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19#c312 |title=Inductees |publisher=Act Sport |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501122434/http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=19 |archivedate= 1 May 2011 |df= }}</ref> In 2011 Roberts was once again president of ACTSport,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=18&tx_ttnews%5Byear%5D=2011&tx_ttnews%5Bmonth%5D=09&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=233&cHash=06361a267edee78e445d9593c05876c7 |title=Press Release |publisher=Act Sport |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426235704/http://www.actsport.com.au/index.php?id=18&tx_ttnews%5Byear%5D=2011&tx_ttnews%5Bmonth%5D=09&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=233&cHash=06361a267edee78e445d9593c05876c7 |archivedate=26 April 2014 |df= }}</ref> and was still in the position in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/afl/afl-news/hirds-status-on-hold-after-debate-20130905-2t8a5.html |title=Hird's status on hold after debate |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald |date= |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>

== Awards and honours ==

In 2000, Roberts was awarded the [[Australian Sports Medal]] for his contribution to the development of sport and recreation in the Australian Capital Territory, his community service as President of ACT Sports House (later ACTSport) and for services to futsal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=978814&search_type=simple&showInd=true |title=It's an Honour - Honours - Search Australian Honours |publisher=Itsanhonour.gov.au |date=2000-10-24 |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>  Also in 2000, he was presented with an achievement award by the CBFS (Brazilian Futsal Confederation) for his contribution to the development of futsal throughout the world. In 2010 Roberts was inducted into the ACT Sport Hall of Fame and has been inducted into the ACT Football Federation Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/cfmedia/docs/annual_report_2011 |title=Annual Report 2011 by Russ Gibbs |publisher=ISSUU |date=2012-03-22 |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>

== Personal life ==

His son PJ is a former professional [[association football|footballer]] and TV pundit in Asia.

